fun_facts:
&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The fastest bird on land, ostriches can sprint up to 43 miles (70 kilometers) per hour.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An average ostrich egg weighs around 3 pounds (about the weight of two dozen chicken eggs!)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ostriches have excellent eyesight. In fact, their eyes are bigger than their brains!&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mountain zebras are the smallest of the zebra subspecies.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are known to be capable climbers, navigating the rocky hillsides of their mountain habitats with ease.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When no water is available in their dry habitats, they will use their sharp, pointed hooves to dig for water beneath the ground surface.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;With just a few hundred individuals remaining, red wolves are among the rarest mammals in the world.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their fearsome reputation, red wolves are normally quite shy around people. They pose little to no threat around humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their home territory can stretch about 200 miles in diameter.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Though they spend most of their lives on the ground, puff adders are adept swimmers and climbers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When scared, puff adders coil into a tight “s” shape. Adults can bite creatures about a third of their length away, but juveniles can launch their entire bodies forward to attack.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;American oystercatchers open clams and other prey by quickly jabbing their bills inside the bivalve’s shell and severing the muscle that pulls the shell halves shut. Then they eat the soft parts inside.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Young chicks will dive and swim underwater to escape predators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their genus name, &lt;em&gt;Haematopus&lt;/em&gt;, comes from the Greek words for “blood foot,” referring to the bird’s bright pink legs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Horseshoe crabs walk along the sea bottom, but they can swim using their gills as paddles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A chemical called hemocyanin makes their blood blue. This is different from hemoglobin, which makes vertebrate blood blue.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Horseshoe crabs glow under ultraviolet light.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Many species of hermit crab get aggressive when they are ready to switch to a larger shell, but striped hermit crabs will cooperate with other members of their species and exchange shells without getting violent.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Females are capable of producing up to 180,000 eggs in a single year.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When they sense danger, they fit their entire bodies inside of their shells to hide.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mummichog was the first fish in space! Two mummichog fish were flown to Skylab in 1973.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They belong to a non-formal group of fish called “killifish” likely from the Dutch word “kill” meaning “stream.” Most killifish live in fresh or brackish water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;“Mummichog” is the Narragansett word for these fish. It means “going in crowds.”&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mummichogs are vulnerable to a fish parasite called fluke.&amp;nbsp;When it infects fish, it makes them thrash near the surface making them more vulnerable to being eaten by a bird, which is the parasite’s next host.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Because they are so easy to care for and so flexible, mummichogs are frequently used in laboratory settings.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pumpkinseeds are an invasive species in Western Europe, where they out-compete native fish. They have been found in Portugal all the way to the southern coast of Ukraine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are also called pond perch, sunfish and punkie.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can hybridize with other members of their genus, including bluegill and green sunfish. Such hybrids are sterile and can’t have offspring.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Wild turkeys are one of only two bird species domesticated from the Americas; the other is the Muscovy duck.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Wild turkeys are an invasive species in New Zealand and Germany.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Wild turkeys rarely fly more than 100 yards (91 meters) but they can fly quickly – up to 54 miles per hour (88.5 kilometers per hour). They can even swim!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Benjamin Franklin wanted the wild turkey to be the country’s national bird instead of the bald eagle. He did not get his wish.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cassowaries have a 5-inch long razor sharp claw on each foot.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cassowaries cannot fly, but they are incredible jumpers and can launch themselves up to 7 feet off the ground!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cassowary&#039;s helmet-like casque is made of keratin, the same material that makes up our hair and fingernails.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;About 1 in 10,000 Ross’s geese are “blue morph” geese that have dark brown necks, backs, and shoulders. Scientists aren’t sure why this happens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A Ross’s goose looks similar to the closely-related snow goose, but can be differentiated by head coloring: the heads of snow geese are often streaked with yellow from where they root in marshland for roots and tubers, while the heads of Ross’s geese remain white because they graze on surface vegetation instead.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This species was described to science in 1770, but not formally classified until 1861. Its Arctic nesting grounds were not discovered until 1938.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like most songbirds, white-throated sparrows have two voiceboxes—called syrinxes—rather than one voicebox, or larynx.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;White-throated sparrows occasionally mate and produce hybrids with dark-eyed juncos. The hybrid offspring look like gray, dull white-throated sparrows with white outer tail feathers like juncos.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are 27 different subspecies of rufous-collared sparrows.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have different vocalizations depending on where they live, almost like regional accents in humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In Costa Rica, this bird is known as &lt;em&gt;come maíz&lt;/em&gt;, or &quot;corn eater.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are the largest North American pigeon.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are closest surviving relatives of the passenger pigeon, a formerly abundant bird whose flocks once stretched across North America before being hunted to extinction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As with other pigeon species, they feed their hatchlings with &quot;pigeon milk,&quot; a white, nutrient-rich substance that parents regurgitate into their babies&#039; mouths.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rose-breasted grosbeaks will visit backyard bird feeders, especially for sunflower seeds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The male rose-breasted grosbeak is sometimes called the “cutthroat bird” due to the bright scarlet patch along its throat and chest.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are in the same family as northern cardinals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female rose-breasted grosbeak females are almost identical to female black-headed grosbeaks; the two species can even interbreed!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ruddy quail-doves are members of the pigeon and dove family and are only distantly related to quails.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They often prefer to walk on the ground instead of flying.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males have a call that sounds like a loud &quot;&lt;em&gt;boop.&lt;/em&gt;&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are members of the &lt;em&gt;Columbidae &lt;/em&gt;family of birds, which includes the common pigeon.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are easily identifiable by their buzzy &quot;zoo-zoo-zoo-zee&quot; song.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males and females look radically different and were originally described as two separate species.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The yellow warbler has more yellow feathers than any other North American warbler.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The yellow warbler’s “&lt;em&gt;seet&lt;/em&gt;” alarm call specifically warns of brown-headed cowbirds, who are notorious nest parasites for warblers and blackbirds. Other birds, particularly the red-wing blackbird, have learned this warning call and the females will rush back to their nests to protect their eggs from being replaced.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female yellow warblers can recognize foreign eggs in their nest. In response, they will rebuild a completely new nest on top of all the eggs and the old nest.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &quot;sandhill&quot;&amp;nbsp;part of their name comes from the Sandhill region of Nebraska.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fossil records show that sandhill cranes have been around for nearly 2.5 million years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are known to build platform nests out of sticks and plants that float on the water&#039;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their name, Tennessee warblers only pass through the U.S. state during their annual migration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They love eating spruce bedworms, and their populations grow significantly where bedworms are plentiful.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their scientific name translates to “weasel-colored woodland thrush.”&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other common names for the wood thrush include the swamp angel, song thrush, or wood robin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The wood thrush is the official bird of Washington, D.C.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Wood thrushes sometimes pick up ants and rub them on their feathers, an activity called “anting.” Scientists aren’t sure why they do this. Some of the ants’ secretions may help protect them from other insects, or it might supplement the birds’ own preen oil.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Redheads can be parasitic brooders. They are known for dropping their eggs in another duck’s nest and leaving their ducklings to be hatched and raised by the other duck.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike many other migratory ducks, redheads tend to fly with erratic shallow wingbeats in groups of unorganized patterns.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While considered a diving duck, redheads will sometimes forage for their food on the water’s surface, like a dabbling duck.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A group of mantellas is called an army.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For many years, scientists thought mantellas of Madagascar were closely related to South America’s poison frogs, which they resemble. However, recent genetic research has shown they are only distantly related but have evolved similar coloration and survival strategy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sanderlings are the only sandpiper with only front-facing toes and no back toes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After foraging up and down sandy beaches, sanderlings sometimes vomit up little sand pellets containing small pieces of shells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are often likened to clockwork toys&amp;nbsp;because of their energetic movements up and down beaches chasing waves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sandpipers in the genus &lt;em&gt;Calidris &lt;/em&gt;are often called “peeps” because of the sound they make.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This duck’s shovel-like bill is lined with comb-like projections called lamellae that allow it to sift through marsh waters for tiny crustaceans and seeds.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These ducks can be seen swimming together in large circles. This is done to stir up the sediment at the bottom of ponds of lakes and unearth tiny animals like&amp;nbsp;crustaceans.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike many species of ducks, northern shovelers are seasonally monogamous. Once a pair bond is formed, they will remain together until the birds leave the breeding grounds in the fall.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have some of the largest ears relative to their body size of all primates. Their ears can move independently!&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have special bacteria in their stomachs that allows them to digest tree gum more easily.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Galagoes are one of the species that practices urine-washing—they urinate into their hands and rub it on their hands and feet. They do this during social grooming, while exploring a new territory, and it may even improve their grip while climbing.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Grasshopper sparrows are one of the new North American sparrows where males have two different songs:&amp;nbsp;one song sounds more like an insect buzz while the other is a series of squeaky notes that males emit while in flight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The grasshopper sparrow prefers to run along the ground rather than fly. It can be very hard to find unless it is singing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The call for which they are named in English — &quot;&lt;em&gt;chick-a-dee-dee-dee&lt;/em&gt;&quot; — is far more complex than it sounds, with information encoded in each note. Generally the more “&lt;em&gt;dees&lt;/em&gt;” that ring out, the greater the threat a predator poses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They hide seeds and other foods to eat later, and can remember thousands of individual hiding places.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Flocks have a dominance hierarchy. Some individuals even belong to several flocks, each with a different ranking.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They will come to bird feeders for sunflower seeds, raisins, fruit, suet and even peanut butter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Birders lovingly call the bird “butter-butt” due to their primrose-hued posteriors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The more colorful males tend to forage higher in trees than females.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its scientific name means “crowned moth-eater.”&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their song sounds like that of the American robin&#039;s, but with a sore throat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The scarlet tanager&#039;s genus name, &lt;em&gt;Piranga&lt;/em&gt;, comes from the Tupi word &lt;em&gt;tijepiranga&lt;/em&gt;, which describes an unknown small bird.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their feet are so small that they cannot walk. They are only capable of scooting sideways on perches.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can beat their wings more than 50 times per second!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During their seasonal migration, they can fly straight across the Gulf of Mexico in a single flight.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sometimes referred to as the northern nomads, northern pintails have extensive migratory routes and have been spotted on every continent except Antarctica.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their slender bodies and 3-foot wingspan allow them to fly great distances at speeds reaching up to 65 miles per hour. This earned them the nickname “the greyhound of the skies.”&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are smallest duck in North America to primarily eat from the water’s surface instead of diving. This technique is known as dabbling.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These ducks are one of the fastest-flying ducks in North America. The&amp;nbsp;fastest recorded green-winged teal hit a speed of 60 miles per hour!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Courtship among green-winged teals occurs in large groups and, at times, up to 35 males may court a single female.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have some of the most elaborate mating “dances” of all ducks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The canvasback was given its common name by early European settlers, who described the male ducks as having a canvas-like color.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This duck’s scientific name was derived from its preferred food: celery root. Celery root’s scientific name is&lt;em&gt; Valisineria americana&lt;/em&gt; and the canvasback’s is &lt;em&gt;Arthya valisineria&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are swift and agile fliers, although they need to get a running start to lift off the ground.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Buffleheads are North America’s smallest diving duck.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These ducks appear to have a large head relative to their small size, which is how they got their name, “bufflehead.”&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The blue-winged teal is one of the latest species to migrate north in the spring but one of the first to head back south in the fall.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Females will choose their nest site by landing in a grassy area and walking around.&amp;nbsp;It can take up to two days before she will find a place suitable to start building her nest.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are often confused with the indigo bunting. However, blue grosbeaks are larger&amp;nbsp;and have chunkier bills.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are close relatives of the Northern cardinal.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It has a soft, wheezy whistle that almost sounds like a squeaky toy with several following notes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The black-bellied whistling duck is monogamous, pairing with the same mate for many years.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their color patterning varies based on what region they are from. Southern song sparrows tend to be paler brown, while northern and coastal residents have dark brown and black streaks in their feathering.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are 24 different subspecies of song sparrows.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cedar waxwings specialize in eating fruit. While they do need protein from insects, their diet is almost entirely fruit-based in winter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are called ‘waxwings’ because some of them produce waxy, bright red appendages on the tip of their secondary wing feathers. The number of waxy tips vary by age and sex, but researchers do not know their purpose.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cedar waxwings have been observed eating overripe berries that have fermented in the sun, which causes the birds to become intoxicated.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some red knots fly over 9,000 miles one-way to get to their coastal wintering grounds in the south. In the spring, they make the same journey north!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;em&gt; rufa &lt;/em&gt;red knot subspecies stops in the Delaware Bay every year during spring migration to feed on horseshoe crab eggs. These eggs give the birds the fuel they need to reach their breeding grounds in the north.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This bird has a feeding habit that&#039;s unique among songbirds: it grips its food with its feet before eating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For a long time, ornithologists&amp;nbsp;considered this bird to be a member of the warbler family. Scientists aren&#039;t totally sure how closely related they are.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;American robins are actually members of the thrush family. Despite sharing a name, they are only distantly related to European robins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;American robins are often thought of as having reddish-orange chests. However, one subspecies in Mexico has a chest that is pale grayish-brown.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Adult males sing a song that sounds like &quot;&lt;em&gt;zee-zee-zee-zooo-zeet&lt;/em&gt;&quot; while courting females.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They use a similar sounding &quot;&lt;em&gt;zoo-zee-zoo-zoo-zee&lt;/em&gt;&quot; song while challenging other males who enter their territory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their genus name, Setophaga, comes from the Greek words for &quot;moth&quot; and &quot;eating.&quot;&amp;nbsp;This is because warblers tend to eat lots of insects.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their squeaky song almost sounds like a rusty wheel turning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This bird is sometimes called the &quot;black-and-white creeper,&quot;&amp;nbsp;due to its habit of creeping along branches while searching for insects to eat.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Another name for this bird is the “mosquito thrush,” due to their feeding habit of snatching insects out of the sky mid-flight.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Six different subspecies of Swainson’s thrushes have been recognized.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To defend their nests, black-necked stilts will perform a “popcorn display,” in which a group of birds surrounds the predator and individual birds hop, jump&amp;nbsp;and flop to confuse and drive it away.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In relation to body size, they have the longest legs compared to any other bird aside from flamingoes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black-necked stilts and American avocets belong to the same family and are capable of producing young together. Those who have documented this cross-hybridization have termed the offspring as “avo-stilts.”&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The plumage on their head and neck changes with the seasons. During the breeding season, the feathers turn a rusty orange color, but in the winter, they are grayish white.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female avocets sometimes lay their eggs in the nests of other female avocets, otherwise known as brood parasitism. These &quot;host&quot; female avocets will incubate the eggs and rear the hatchlings as if they were their own.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Adults have long, upturned black bills. Males tend to have less of a curve compared to females.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a migratory bird, they fly huge distances from their breeding grounds to their wintering sites. Some have been known to travel 6,500 miles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are fast travelers, flying at speeds averaging 27-47 miles per hour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They use their beaks to flip over rocks and shells to look for food. Sometimes several birds work together to flip larger objects.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In parts of the Midwest, this bird is called the yellow bandit.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males sing their &lt;em&gt;wichety wichety wichety wich&lt;/em&gt; song to establish territory and attract females.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like many other warblers, they migrate mostly at nighttime.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Baltimore orioles look&amp;nbsp;similar to an orchard oriole, but there&#039;s an easy way to tell them apart: Baltimore orioles have vibrant orange coloring on their bellies, while orchard orioles are more of a chestnut brown.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Baltimore orioles get their name because their coloring resembles the coat-of-arms of the 17th century Lord Baltimore.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There is a famous Major League Baseball team named after this bird.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There&amp;nbsp;are seven recognized subspecies of Carolina wren.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They belong to the &lt;em&gt;Troglodyte&lt;/em&gt; family which means “cave dweller.” They don’t necessarily live in caves, though they do nest in tree cavities.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are generally not aggressive toward other species. They nest near Baltimore orioles, robins, chipping sparrows and kingbirds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They don’t tend to visit backyard seed feeders but will sometimes visit nectar feeders or those with fruits and jelly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When they fly, they tend to stick close to the ground, never flying above the tree canopy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name &quot;vireo&quot; comes from a Latin word meaning &quot;I am green.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Only adults have the red eye color that gives this species its name.&amp;nbsp;Juveniles have brown eyes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to Guinness World Records, the red-eyed vireo holds the record for most number of songs per unit time for a bird species, with 22,197 songs recorded in a 10-hour period.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Winter flocks can comprise several million birds, including other blackbird species and starlings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Intruders beware! These birds are territorial. Male red-winged blackbirds will chase out intruders of any size if they wander too close to a nest.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Barred parakeets form flocks of hundreds of individuals that often fly above mountain clouds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are often kept as pets because of their even-tempered and sociable natures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are especially fond of bamboo seeds.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Not all white-eyed vireos migrate. Some populations that live in the southern parts of the U.S., especially around the Gulf Coast, stay there year-round.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Juvenile members of this species actually have dark gray eyes. They do not develop white irises until they reach adulthood.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are six subspecies of white-eyed vireo.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ovenbirds gets their&amp;nbsp;name from the dome-shaped nest that it builds, which resembles a mud oven.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike many other warblers, ovenbirds walk&amp;nbsp;on the forest floor, rather than hop, while looking for food.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A male may learn around 200 songs throughout its life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Both males and females sing a varied, repetitive song that can be heard all day—and sometimes all night—during the spring and summer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can incorporate non-bird noises they hear into their songs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mockingbirds are very territorial. They will chase off much larger animals, including humans,&amp;nbsp;if they think their nests are being threatened.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During migration, some semipalmated sandpipers double their weight, so they can have enough energy to fuel their long-distance migrations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some semipalmated sandpipers make nonstop flights over the Atlantic Ocean from the northeast coast of North America to South America, a distance of up to 2000 miles (about 3200 kilometers).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males court females by splashing in the water and blowing bubbles with their bills.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During the summer months, adult males sport deep brown feathers and a bright blue bill.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like other migratory species indigo buntings migrate at night, using the stars for navigation!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They often build their nests near roadsides, power lines and train tracks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They frequently join foraging flocks of chickadees during their migration. The “chickadee-dee-dee” call is a possible marker for the presence of the magnolia warbler.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ornithologist Alexander Wilson first recorded the magnolia warbler in 1811. He named the species after the magnolia tree that he found it in, even though they prefer other types of trees.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name &quot;dunlin&quot; comes from its winter plumage, a dull brown-gray color often called dun. As far back as 1531, they were called “dunling,”&amp;nbsp;which means “little brown one.”&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dunlin flocks can fly up to 45 to 55 miles (72 to 88 kilometers) per hour.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their ability to mimic vocalizations of other species may help males impress mates. A bird with a big vocabulary would have survived several years and, therefore, would make a good mate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Catbirds’ calls are often confused with cats’ meows.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their genus name, &lt;em&gt;Dumetella&lt;/em&gt;, means “little thicket” in Latin, and reflects where they like to live.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Occasionally vagrant Eurasian wigeons will show up in the middle of a flock of American wigeons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;American wigeons have been known to follow other diving ducks to steal away their food, leading to them sometimes being called robber ducks or poacher ducks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name &quot;semipalmated&quot;&amp;nbsp;comes from their partially-webbed toes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their bill is incredibly strong. They sometimes use it to hammer into rocky sand and gravel to probe for food.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Eastern sub-species is called the yellow palm warbler and in the spring it&amp;nbsp;migrates east of the Appalachian mountains, while the Western palm warbler migrates through the Mississippi Valley.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their name, palm warblers do not actually build their nests in palm trees. Their name is associated with the palm trees of Hispaniola, the Caribbean island where the earliest specimens were collected.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They bob their tails up and down while foraging for food.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pygmy slow lorises are the only known venomous primate. Modified sweat glands near their elbows allow pygmy slow lorises to secrete a toxin. When they’re alarmed, they can lick these glands, spreading the toxin to their teeth. Their venom can incapacitate predators as large as humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pygmy slow lorises sleep curled up in a ball with their head between their knees and their legs hooked over their head.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their large eyes give them phenomenal vision, even in dim light in a forest. In fact, bright light can be hugely disorienting and distressing for them.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eastern screech-owls can rotate their heads 270 degrees. They have 14 vertebrae in their necks (humans have only 7)!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have asymmetrical ear openings. One ear is higher than the other to help them pinpoint sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These owls are opportunistic eaters. If they think they can eat it, they will try.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Most cats have vertical slit-like pupils, but Pallas’ cats have round pupils.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When they are excited or scared, they make a sound much more like the yelp of a small dog than any typical cat sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When Pallas&#039; cats&amp;nbsp;were first discovered, some naturalists mistakenly thought they were the wild ancestors of domestic Persian cats, because they&amp;nbsp;look so alike.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are often described as smelling like buttered popcorn&amp;nbsp;because their urine contains 2-acetyl-1-pyrroline, the chemical compound that gives popcorn its aroma.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Baby binturongs are called binlets.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have extremely long tails which they use to balance when moving along tree limbs.&amp;nbsp; They use their tails to grasp branches and even to lower themselves.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their lower&amp;nbsp;teeth form a &quot;tooth comb,&quot; which they use to groom their hair.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They eat fruit&amp;nbsp;and help disperse&amp;nbsp;fruit seeds&amp;nbsp;around the forests where they live.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Northern snakeheads have sacs above their gills that absorb and store oxygen from air, allowing them to survive out of water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Snakeheads can also &quot;walk&quot; on land, moving their head and back fin in opposite directions to propel them forward.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Snakehead fish are carnivores with dagger-like teeth, making them dangerous predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pale stripes on the spiny-tailed monitor&#039;s neck distinguish it from two similar-looking subspecies that occupy the same range.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It can defend&amp;nbsp;itself with its spiny tail, which can&amp;nbsp;be wielded like a club.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When threatened, these lizards will hide inside the cracks of rocks and fill&amp;nbsp;their lungs with air to wedge themselves in place.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their eggs are large&amp;nbsp;with leathery shells.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When they retreat into their shells, spotted pond turtles make a soft croak.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can grow up to 16 inches long.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Geckos are the only lizards that produce more than a hiss or other simple sound. Their vocalizations range from squeaks and clicks to barks and croaks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Adhesive scales, called lemellae, on a day gecko&#039;s toes help it&amp;nbsp;cling to smooth surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Iranian gecko can detach its tail to distract a predator while it makes an escape.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When frightened, the Iranian gecko will push itself onto the tips of its toes and hiss or squeal.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Guinea pigs have no tails.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Only about 4% of their day is spent sleeping, and they only sleep for about 6 minutes at a time.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Scientists can look at hormones to determine whether a crocodile monitor is male or female.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The crocodile monitor can use its powerful tail&amp;nbsp;like a whip for defense.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is believed that emperor tamarins were named after German emperor Wilhelm II.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their long, white whiskers resemble a mustache.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Home&#039;s hinge-back tortoises require&amp;nbsp;high humidity, which is unusual compared to most other tortoise species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They mostly eat insects, which is also unique to this tortoise species.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pancake tortoises have thin, flat shells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They seem to get most of their water from the foods they eat.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their name, these lizards are not true chameleons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are insectivorous, meaning they eat insects.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A male tomistoma can grow to be 16 feet long!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There&#039;s no evidence to suggest that tomistoma parents care for their young after they hatch, which is unusual for crocodilians.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males have a colorful flap of skin underneath their chin, called a dewlap, which they can extend to appear larger and more threatening.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Timber rattlesnakes are skilled climbers and have been discovered in trees at heights of more than 80 feet.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have many common names throughout their range, including American viper, black rattlesnake, eastern rattlesnake, timber rattler and canebrake&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alligator lizards typically live 130 feet above the forest floor.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males tend to have more vibrant colors than females.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is estimated that most coral reefs are between 5,000 and 10,000 years old, with some actually tracing their beginnings back 50 million years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Coral reefs form as live polyps built not only on each other, but also on the skeleton remains of previous corals. As a result, they are able to create massive structures like the Great Barrier Reef.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A colony can grow to hundreds of thousands of individual polyps.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Of all the boas, constrictors can live&amp;nbsp;in the greatest variety of habitats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are named for their method of predation: constriction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The wood duck&#039;s home range changes with the rise and fall of floodwaters.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The duck&#039;s young remain in the nest for just 24 hours after hatching.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When scared or excited, the hawk-headed parrot can raise its nape&amp;nbsp;feathers, forming a fan around its head.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are much smaller than other common Amazonian parrots.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These tortoises are named for the shape of their scutes, which are impressed or indented.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They spend most of their time under leaves on the forest floor.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chinese three-striped box turtles are semi-aquatic.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Three dark stripes on its shell give it its common name.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are eight subspecies of beach mice, five of which live along the Gulf Coast.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Beach mice are monogamous and pair for life.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The giant cloud rat&#039;s large hind feet and long claws make it an excellent climber.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is endemic to the island of Luzon in the Philippines.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The rhinoceros snake gets its name from the scaly &quot;horn&quot; on the tip of its snout.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In rare instances, a rhinoceros snake will keep its steel gray, subadult coloring rather than turning the typical blue-green.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Juvenile Taylor&#039;s cantils have a yellow-tipped tail for luring prey. Adults lose this feature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These snakes lose their coloration, becoming darker as they age.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chinese crocodile lizards&amp;nbsp;frequently enter&amp;nbsp;into a metabolic pause, where they&amp;nbsp;remain&amp;nbsp;motionless and unresponsive to stimuli for several hours at a time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reptile is sometimes referred to as the &quot;lizard of great sleepiness&quot; by indigenous people.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Australian snake-necked turtles are named for their long, narrow necks!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These turtles burrow under fallen leaves and&amp;nbsp;estivate, or become dormant, when conditions get too hot or dry.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Eastern box turtles are the official reptiles of Tennessee and North Carolina. They were nearly the state reptile of Pennsylvania as well.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Box turtles generally live for 25-35 years but have been known to survive to over 100 years old!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Though they may be best known for hopping, wallabies, kangaroos and wallaroos can also crawl and swim!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In general, wallabies tend to be smaller than kangaroos and &lt;span&gt;wallaroos&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and can be distinguished by their darker muzzle and paws.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fly River turtles are also called pig-nosed turtles, because of their large, fleshy snouts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similar to soft-shelled turtles, leathery skin covers the Fly River turtle&#039;s shell.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Banded rock rattlesnakes&amp;nbsp;use venom to subdue their prey before swallowing it whole.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Corn snakes are constrictors, wrapping themselves around prey to squeeze and subdue it before swallowing it whole.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name corn snake may have originated from the markings on this snake&#039;s belly, which resemble maize, or&amp;nbsp;Indian corn.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The eastern diamondback rattlesnake is North America&#039;s longest, heaviest venomous snake!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Light reflected&amp;nbsp;off of this snake&#039;s keeled scales makes its skin appear dull, rather than shiny.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Goeldi&#039;s monkeys can reportedly leap a horizontal distance of about 13 feet without losing height.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike any other New World monkey, &lt;span&gt;Goeldi&#039;s&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are known to rely heavily on mushrooms during the dry season when fruit is scarce.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chameleons can move each eye independently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Meller&#039;s chameleons can extend their tongues up to 20 inches (51 centimeters) to catch prey.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A female&amp;nbsp;can give birth to a litter of four to 25 joeys that are each about the size of a kidney bean.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Opossums are known for playing dead when they feel threatened, but this behavior is more typical of young opossums.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The green aracari&#039;s bill has a serrated edge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green aracaris are named for the dark green feathers found on their backs, throughout their wings and into their tails.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The green aracari&#039;s bill has a serrated edge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green aracaris are named for the dark green feathers found on their backs, throughout their wings and into their tails.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;The electric eel is a &lt;span&gt;knifefish&lt;/span&gt; and is more closely related to catfish and carp than to other eel families.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span&gt;They&amp;nbsp;are capable of generating up to 800 volts of electricity!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The northern pine snake is an efficient digger and spends a significant amount of time in underground burrows.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These snakes reach a maximum length of about 6 feet (1.8 meters).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Two short, scaly tentacles extend from this snake&#039;s snout, giving it its common name.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This aquatic species herds passing prey by&amp;nbsp;&quot;bumping&quot; out part of its body. The resulting bow wave causes the prey to change course, often heading straight toward the snake&#039;s mouth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sinaloan milk snakes exhibit aposematic mimicry; they are not venomous, but their&amp;nbsp;color patterns resemble those of a venomous snake.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The common name &quot;milk snake&quot; originated from the false belief that these snakes milked cows.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mangrove snake has rear fangs and is mildly venomous.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The mangrove snake&#039;s eyes are large with narrow, vertical slits, earning it another common name—the yellow-ringed cat snake.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This lizard is named for its large, heavy scales that resemble those of the caiman crocodile.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Caiman lizards can both climb and swim to&amp;nbsp;escape predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This species is named for its ability to flatten its neck&amp;nbsp;to appear larger, resembling a cobra.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The false water cobra is semi-aquatic and can climb, burrow and swim.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These frogs spend much of their time burrowed under leaves and mud.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can inflate themselves to deter predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red salamanders can extend and withdraw their projectile tongues in 11 milliseconds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have glands that produce a toxic secretion to repel predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;New Caledonian geckos are the largest known gecko species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When threatened, these geckos can detach (and later regenerate)&amp;nbsp;their tails.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Matamata turtles prefer the&amp;nbsp;soft, muddy bottoms of slow-moving, shallow bodies of water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite being an aquatic species, &lt;span&gt;matamatas&lt;/span&gt; are not well adapted for swimming in open water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Matamata turtles prefer the&amp;nbsp;soft, muddy bottoms of slow-moving, shallow bodies of water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite being an aquatic species, &lt;span&gt;matamatas&lt;/span&gt; are not well adapted for swimming in open water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The snake&#039;s rattling sound is created through the rapid vibration of a series of loose-fitting, interlocking scales at the base of the tail.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lance head rattlesnakes yield a fairly large amount of venom per bite—about 80 to 100 milligrams.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fiji banded iguanas are arboreal and spend most of their time in trees.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These lizards are named for the blue or light green stripes that males exhibit.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Asian water dragons are strong swimmers and, if necessary, can remain submerged for&amp;nbsp;up to&amp;nbsp;25 minutes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males and females sometimes express aggressive behavior toward each other in the form of arm waving, puffing up of the throat, head bobbing and chasing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fringed flaps on the leaf-tailed gecko&#039;s sides and&amp;nbsp;lower jaws flatten against a surface, obscuring their outline. The increased surface area reflects and refracts light, aiding their camouflage capabilities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If disturbed, the leaf-tailed gecko&amp;nbsp;opens its jaws wide, exposing a bright red mouth and emitting a loud distress call that resembles a child&#039;s scream.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green tree monitors reach lengths of about&amp;nbsp;3 feet, with tails twice the length of their bodies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Females reportedly use termite mounds as nesting chambers, because the temperature and moisture conditions create an ideal incubator.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Basilisks can run on their hind legs. Their speed, coupled with specialized scales on their feet, allows them to sprint&amp;nbsp;across the water&#039;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green crested basilisks can remain submerged underwater&amp;nbsp;for more than 10 minutes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alligator snapping turtles are the largest freshwater turtles in the world.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An appendage on the alligator snapping turtle&#039;s tongue resembles a worm, helping this ambush predator&amp;nbsp;lure prey.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Coatis have been called &quot;coatimundi&quot; or &quot;coati-mondi&quot; meaning &quot;lone coati&quot; in Guarani, a native language of Brazil. The name came about as a result of biologists describing solitary male coatis that they believed at the time to be a separate species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The coati&#039;s semi-prehensile tail is used for balance and is often held erect above the body.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Persian onager is the largest subspecies of Asiatic wild ass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Even though their native habitat can reach an incredibly hot 120 degrees Fahrenheit, these hardy animals can adapt to bitter cold temperatures by growing a dense, curly winter coat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ancient civilizations attempted to domesticate the onager without success due to the animal&#039;s unruly nature. The onager&#039;s relative, the African wild ass, is the ancestor of domestic donkeys.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The white-naped crane is a popular symbol of the Korean New Year celebration and commonly featured in art and folklore.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cranes are the tallest of all flying birds and are found on every continent, except Antarctica and South America.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red siskins were deliberately hybridized with domestic canaries in the early twentieth century to create the &quot;red factor&quot; variety of canary.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The red siskin&#039;s vocalization a series of trills and chatters with&amp;nbsp;a raspy jut-jut call.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The red-crowned crane is named for the red &quot;cap&quot; on top of its head, which is exposed red skin. These cranes are considered sacred in Japan, where they are considered a sign of fidelity in marriage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On average, red-crowned cranes are the heaviest crane species, weighing up to 25 pounds.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Guam kingfisher utters its first call of the morning at about the same time every day, usually at dawn. It does this with such regularity that, according to local belief, the bird can be used to tell time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This bird makes its nest in a tree by jabbing repeatedly at the tree&#039;s bark with its sharp beak while flying.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The upper edge of the loggerhead shrike&#039;s hooked bill features a pair of&amp;nbsp;pointy projections, called &quot;tomial teeth.&quot; Like a falcon, the shrike tackles prey with a precise attack to the nape, probably using these &quot;teeth&quot; to paralyze the animal with a jab to the spinal cord.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Loggerhead shrikes eat the heads and abdomens of toxic lubber grasshoppers but discard the insect&#039;s poisonous thorax.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Newly fledged loggerhead shrikes perform exaggerated, misdirected versions of adult hunting behavior. They peck at inanimate objects, fly about with leaves or sticks in their beaks, practice aerial chases without a target and perform rudimentary impaling gestures.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hooded crane&#039;s latin name, Grus monacha, translates to &quot;nun crane.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hooded cranes nest in such remote forested wetlands in southeastern Siberia that it was not until 1974 that biologists located the first nest.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fossil records place cranes in Nebraska more than 9 million years ago.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Guam rails can only fly about 3 to 10 feet (1 to 3 meters) at a time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In their native Guam, these birds&amp;nbsp;are called ko&#039;ko&#039;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Male Eld&#039;s deer are offered large jolly balls during rutting season. They spend a lot of time pushing the balls around with their antlers, much like they would trees and shrubs in the wild.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eld&#039;s deer breeding season is triggered by day length. The deer breed in the spring when day length increases, unlike white-tailed deer that breed in the fall as day length shortens.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Patagonian maras&amp;nbsp;may walk, hop in a rabbit-like fashion, gallop or&amp;nbsp;&lt;span&gt;stot&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;— a unique form of locomotion typically exhibited by ungulates, where the animal bounces on all fours.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These maras travel in mated pairs, with the male aggressively protecting his mate from rivals and predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These heavy-bodied lizards are the Grand Cayman’s largest native land vertebrate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This species of “rock iguana” can exceed 5 feet (1.5 meters) in length (nose to tail tip) and weigh more than 25 pounds (11 kilograms).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Orangutan means &quot;person of the forest&quot; in the Indonesian and Malaysian&amp;nbsp;languages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Orangutans have cognitive maps, often returning to the same feeding sites they have visited in the past to forage for fruit, insects and flowers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The primary locomotion of an orangutan is known as &quot;arboreal clambering.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Orangutan means &quot;person of the forest&quot; in the Indonesian and Malaysian&amp;nbsp;languages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Orangutans have cognitive maps, often returning to the same feeding sites they have visited in the past to forage for fruit, insects and flowers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The primary locomotion of an orangutan is known as &quot;arboreal clambering.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Poison frogs are commonly called poison arrow and poison dart frogs due to the indigenous community reportedly rubbing their arrow tips on the frogs&#039; backs before hunting. However, only three species have been documented as actually being used for this purpose, including the golden poison frog, the most toxic of all frog species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All three of these documented species belong to the genus Phyllobates and not Dendrobates, the genus that includes the most brightly colored of poison frogs that are most often recognized as &quot;poison dart frogs.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Poison frogs are commonly called poison arrow and poison dart frogs due to the indigenous community reportedly rubbing their arrow tips on the frogs&#039; backs before hunting. However, only three species have been documented as actually being used for this purpose, including the golden poison frog, the most toxic of all frog species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All three of these documented species belong to the genus Phyllobates and not Dendrobates, the genus that includes the most brightly colored of poison frogs that are most often recognized as &quot;poison dart frogs.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word tanager comes from the Brazilian Tupi Indian word &quot;tangara.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word tanager comes from the Brazilian Tupi Indian word &quot;tangara.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A stingray&#039;s spine is constantly being shed and replaced. At times, they may even have two at a once.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although docile creatures, they inflict more human injuries yearly than any other animal in Amazonian rivers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Individuals in a litter of stingrays are called pups.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A stingray&#039;s spine is constantly being shed and replaced. At times, they may even have two at a once.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although docile creatures, they inflict more human injuries yearly than any other animal in Amazonian rivers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Individuals in a litter of stingrays are called pups.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A stingray&#039;s spine is constantly being shed and replaced. At times, they may even have two at a once.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although docile creatures, they inflict more human injuries yearly than any other animal in Amazonian rivers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Individuals in a litter of stingrays are called pups.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Even with eight eyes, the Goliath bird-eating tarantula doesn&#039;t see much. It uses the hairs on its legs and abdomen to sense vibrations on the ground or in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While their name has the term &quot;bird-eating&quot; in it, they don&#039;t eat birds frequently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Goliath bird-eating tarantula makes noise by rubbing bristles on its legs together. This hissing noise, called stridulation, is loud enough to be heard up to 15 feet away.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The gray tree frog&#039;s scientific name is&amp;nbsp;Hyla versicolor, which comes from the Latin for &quot;variable color.&quot;&amp;nbsp;It is named for its ability to alter its skin color based on the time of day and surrounding temperature. The skin becomes much lighter at night and darker during the day.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The gray tree frog hibernates in the winter by taking refuge in trees. It survives freezing temperatures by producing glycerol to &quot;freeze&quot; itself while maintaining interior metabolic processes at a very slow rate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Banded leporinus have been observed jumping.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name tarantula&amp;nbsp;originated in the Renaissance period and referred to a small wolf spider from Taranto, Italy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;Pink-toed tarantulas can throw hairs from their body as a form of defense.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pelcostomus are sometimes referred to as &quot;janitor fish&quot; for their ability to clean tank algae.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males guard the eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Piranhas play an important role in their natural environment. As both predators and scavengers, their presence in an ecosystem can affect the distribution of other species of fish.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A good portion of their diet consists of fins nipped from the tails of larger fish.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males compete for breeding access to females, and fights sometimes result in one male turning another over on to their backs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They frequently reach ages of 50 years or more.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Males and females use head movements as signals to identify each other.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The red-crested cardinal has been featured on postage stamps in its native countries of Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a common sight in Hawaii and Puerto Rico, where it has been introduced.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Arowanas are related to primitive fishes and are sometimes called the &quot;bony-tongued fish.&quot; &quot;Osteoglossum&quot; means &quot;bony tongue&quot; and &quot;bicirrhosum&quot; means &quot;two barbels.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Male fish help care for their young by carrying eggs, larvae and early juveniles in their mouths until the yolk sac has been absorbed, which takes about two months.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite being nearly immobile on the forest floor—they drag their bodies across the ground—they are surprisingly competent swimmers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Food remains in their relatively short digestive tract for about one month.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their metabolisms are so slow that sloths typically only defecate once a week, lowering themselves to the base of their tree to do so.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite being nearly immobile on the forest floor—they drag their bodies across the ground—they are surprisingly competent swimmers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Food remains in their relatively short digestive tract for about one month.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their metabolisms are so slow that sloths typically only defecate once a week, lowering themselves to the base of their tree to do so.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If a predator approaches a nest of baby chicks, one of the parents will pretend to have a broken wing to distract the hunter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The oldest sunbittern on record (at any North American zoo) lived until age 33 and was on exhibit in Amazonia at the Smithsonian&#039;s National Zoo.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sunbittern is the only member of the Eurypygidae family.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Consuming wood as a primary energy source is extremely rare among vertebrates. Fish in the genus&amp;nbsp;Farlowella&amp;nbsp;are the only known fish evolved to do this.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They do not attempt to hide their eggs in caves or crevices, instead opting to lay them in open water. Males guard fertilized eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Yellow-spotted Amazon River turtles can live up to 70 years.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Yellow-spotted Amazon River turtles can live up to 70 years.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A whooping crane&#039;s trachea coils about 9 inches (23 centimeters) into their sternum while calling, which allows for increased volume and variation in pitch.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While whooping crane hatchlings cannot fly, they can swim to escape predators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Operation Migration, a program assigned with the task of helping cranes learn migratory paths, helps conserve whooping cranes by leading migrations with an ultralight aircraft.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden lion tamarins move quadrupedally through the trees and can spring and leap between branches and vines.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the early 1970s, there were as few as 200 golden lion tamarins in the wild. They were upgraded from critically endangered to endangered in 2003 following intensive conservation efforts. About one-third of the wild population today originated from golden lion tamarins raised in human care.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sand cats have dense hair and pads on the soles of each foot that protect against the intense heat and cold of their habitat, as well as aiding in movement across the sand. The pads help them navigate across shifting sands.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sand cats are fearless snake hunters—their prey can include venomous vipers and other snakes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a predator approaches banded mongooses, they bunch together and move as a group, creating the appearance of a single large animal. The individuals in front may even stand on their hind legs and make snapping lunges toward the predator.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The more social mongoose species tend to be smaller than the solitary species.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Brush-tailed bettongs rarely, if ever, drink water or eat green plant matter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Brush-tailed bettongs&#039; tails are prehensile, which allows for collection of materials for nesting.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Individual brush-tailed bettongs dig&amp;nbsp;38 to 115 investigatory holes each night, which equates to each individual moving about 6 tons of soil each year.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Howlers make up the highest percentage of the primates in the areas that they occupy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black howler monkeys are one of the few primate species with different coat colors in males and females. Males have a black coat, while females are blonde.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black-footed ferrets are very playful, especially as juveniles. Young at play will wrestle, arch their backs and hop backward with their mouths wide open, in a display known as the &quot;ferret dance.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Once thought extinct, an isolated population of black-footed ferrets was discovered. Eighteen wild animals were caught to establish a breeding colony, from which all wild black-footed ferrets are now descended.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black-footed ferrets are North America&#039;s only native ferret species&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dwarf mongooses will forage with hornbills. Hornbills catch insects, rodents and other prey flushed by the pack and in return serve as lookouts, sounding alarm calls when avian predators are sighted.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hornbills will gather at termite mounds where their mongoose packs spend&amp;nbsp;the night and wait for them to emerge, sometimes even providing wake up calls. If hornbills fail to appear, mongooses hesitate to leave their refuge and begin foraging.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Extreme panting helps fennec foxes keep their temperatures regulated when the heat climbs; breathing rates climb from 23 breaths per minute to up to 690.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their diminutive stature, fennec foxes are surprisingly good at jumping. Adults can jump up to 3 feet (1 meter) when standing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When threatened, greater Madagascar tenrecs can roll up completely in a ball, tucking their head and limbs toward their belly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When they&#039;re alarmed, tenrecs produce a pusling keen. This sound is barely audible, and is delivered as a chain of pulses at a rate of eight per second.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tenrecs retain characteristics that were perhaps more widespread in early placental mammals, including a low and variable body temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Many people confuse lesser tenrecs with a species of African hedgehog found in pet stores but these are not the same animals; hedgehogs are members of a different order.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Przewalski&#039;s horses have 66 chromosomes, compared to the 64 that domestic horses have. It is unusual in that they can produce fertile hybrids with the domestic horse (65 chromosomes) that are able to breed and produce offspring. The hybrids look like Przewalski&#039;s horses, and the only way to identify them is through chromosome testing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Przewalski&#039;s horses are called &quot;takhi,&quot; which means &quot;spirit&quot; in Mongolia.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red ruffed lemurs (and lemurs in general) have a tooth comb and a grooming claw that is used for grooming fur.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Even though they don&#039;t encounter venomous&amp;nbsp;snakes in the wild, red ruffed lemurs at the Duke Primate Center developed a venomous snake call in the presence of copperheads. They can also understand the alarm calls of black-and-white ruffed lemurs, which live in a different part of Madagascar.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Titi monkeys have been seen chewing leaves and then rubbing the pulp on their chest. The reason for this is unknown.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tail entwining—when two individuals sit with their tails wrapped around each other—is used to reinforce bonds amongst pairs. Tail twining is especially common between the adult male and female and takes place when two family members are sitting together. This is true whether the monkeys are awake or asleep.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Short-eared elephant shrews clean themselves with dust baths.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their long tails are lined with knobbed bristles. The exact function of the bristles&amp;nbsp;is unknown, but they may be used like swabs to spread their scent.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One member of the group will act as a sentinel, on the lookout for predators. The sentry will stand on its hind legs, often using its tail as support, or perch in a bush or tree, scanning for danger. Individuals rotate sentinel duty throughout the day.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A group of meerkats is called a mob.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their upper incisors grow continuously and look like small tusks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite looking like rodents, their closest relatives are actually elephants and manatees.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hyraxes consistently urinate in the same place, and the large amounts of calcium carbonate in their urine turns the cliffs where they live white. The calcium carbonate crystals were used as medicine, both by several African tribes as well as by Europeans, to treat such ailments as epilepsy, hysteria and various injuries.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One of the most notable characteristics of this animal is its defense system; striped skunks have the ability to spray a foul smelling fluid from two glands located near the base of the tail. This oily musk, expelled through the anus, can cause temporary blindness and pain if sprayed in the eyes of a potential attacker. Juvenile skunks are capable of spraying at 8 days old, around two weeks before their eyes open.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red-rumped agoutis make a significant contribution to the forestation of their natural habitat; they are the only mammal species within their native range&amp;nbsp;known to be able to open a Brazil nut husk.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black-tailed prairie dogs are actually a species of ground squirrel, named &quot;dog&quot; because of their alarm bark.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The largest prairie dog colony ever recorded spanned over 25,000 square miles (65,000 square kilometers) and was home to an estimated 400 million prairie dogs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Burrowing owls are the only small owl species to perch on the ground. Rather than fly away, they&amp;nbsp;often run or flatten themselves against the ground when disturbed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While still in the nest, a burrowing owlet&#039;s distress cry mimics the sound of a rattlesnake, scaring away predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Damaraland mole rats dig with their protuberant lower incisors and forefeet. Their large lower incisors can move separately.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like naked mole-rats, Damaraland mole rats exhibit co-operative breeding, where some individuals forgo reproduction to help others breed. This type of reproduction is most common among insects like honeybees.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If a predator grabs a degu by the tail, a ring of thin skin at the tail&#039;s base will tear off, allowing the degu to escape. There is very little blood loss and the wound heals quickly, although the tail will not grow back.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Degus sand bathe by marking an area of sand with urine and rolling around in it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tamarins and marmosets are the among the only monkeys or apes that regularly give birth to twins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Scientists suggest that marmosets have evolved to take advantage of an insect diet, and as a part of the process have become smaller.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden-headed lion tamarins move quadrupedally through the main canopy of the forest. When climbing down tree trunks, they can move with their heads or tails downward.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tamarins play a significant role in seed dispersal; many of the fruits they eat have seeds that pass through the monkey&#039;s digestive tract unharmed and end up deposited well away from the parent plant.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;La Plata three-banded armadillos are the only armadillo to rely heavily on their armor. Some other armadillo species cannot roll up because they have too many plates to curl.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They do not dig burrows like most armadillos, but use the abandoned burrows of anteaters when they can get them.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Larger Malay mouse-deer are known as &quot;living fossils&quot; because they have changed little in 30 million years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When standing on all fours, their hindquarters are taller than their front end.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chinchillas&#039; teeth are dark orange.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their fur is so dense that up to 60 hairs can grow out of one follicle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Malagasy giant jumping rats are the largest rodent native to Madagascar; they are found nowhere else on Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is the only living species of its genus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can jump nearly 40 inches into the air when threatened.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Naked mole-rats are not completely hairless. They have sensory whiskers on their faces and on their tails, and they have hairs between their toes that allow their feet to function as brooms with which they sweep soil.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike most other mammals, they cannot maintain a steady body temperature. They keep warm by huddling together and by basking in warmer shallow tunnels.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Naked mole-rats are the longest-living rodents in the world! In fact, the Zoo has two distinct habitats: one habitat is for geriatric mole-rats approaching 30 years old, and one&amp;nbsp;multistory habitat is for younger mole-rats.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tree shrews were once placed in the order formerly known as Insectivora, and then classified as primates for 50 years. Recent research distinguishes them from both orders and they are now classified in the order Scandentia, the only family in that order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tree shrews have a symbiotic relationship with pitcher plants, a group of plants with large, tube-shaped flowers.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pale-headed saki monkeys have been known to cover 33 feet (10 meters) in a single bound when escaping from danger.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These porcupines use their prehensile tail to grasp! Half of the weight of the tail is composed of muscle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It could&amp;nbsp;take up to six months to determine a prehensile-tailed porcupine&#039;s sex, because its sexual organs are internal. Instead, Zoo scientists use the innovative technique of analyzing DNA extracted from a quill to rapidly determine the sex.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At night, Prevost&#039;s squirrels rest in hollows in trees or on tree branches in nests built of leaves and twigs. They wrap their tails around them at night for warmth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike ground squirrels, tree squirrels do not hibernate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rock cavies have heavily padded feet and blunt nails, rather than the well-developed sharp nails found in other genera in this family. These adaptations help them move on slick rock surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are surprisingly agile climbers; they do most of their foraging in trees and can leap from boulder to boulder.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Screaming hairy armadillos consume large amounts of sand while foraging for food; accounts of 50 percent of an armadillo&#039;s stomach contents being filled with sand have been recorded.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Screaming hairy armadillos do not need to drink water regularly; efficient kidneys and the ability to retain moisture in the plants that they consume allow them to go long periods without drinking.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tamanduas, and all anteaters, belong to the suborder Vermilingua, which literally means &quot;worm-tongue,&quot; describing their famous long tongues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The underside of their tails is fur-less; this allows them to grip tree branches more securely as they move through the trees.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Von der Decken hornbills are named a German explorer, Baron Karl Klaus von der Decken, who wrote about the species while exploring in Africa.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Spoonbills fly in long diagonal lines with their necks and legs completely stretched out.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is thought that the roseate spoonbill receives its bright coloring from the pigments of the crustaceans that it eats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When it walks, the roseate spoonbill swings its head back and forth in a sideways motion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Not all elephants develop visible tusks. In Asian elephants, only some males have large, prominent tusks. Most female and some male Asian elephants have small tusks, called tushes, which seldom protrude more than an inch or two from the lip line.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Elephants communicate over long distances using low-pitched sounds that are barely audible to humans. These powerful infrasonic rumbles contain specific messages that can be heard and understood by other elephants more than 2&amp;nbsp;miles away.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At times, when its pond dries up, the African clawed frog can burrow in the mud and may lay dormant for up to a year.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The African clawed frog was the first vertebrate cloned in a laboratory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their skin produces a type of antibiotic that heals wounds rapidly, presumably a useful adaptation in the stagnant, microbe-filled waters where they live.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like all amphibians, caecilians breathe primarily through their skin but will occasionally come to the surface to breathe air through their lungs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aquatic caecilians have a sensory organ in the form of a tentacle that lies on the upper jaw behind the nostril and carries chemical messages.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The arapaima&#039;s mouth works like a vacuum. When hungry, it opens its mouth to suck up nearby food.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This fish can breathe air and stay submerged for 10-20 minutes at a time. It can survive up to 24 hours outside of the water!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Barred tiger salamanders are one of the longest terrestrial salamanders in North America, and possibly in the world.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pacu is a fruit-eating relative of the piranha and is often mistaken as one in the pet trade.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pacu&#039;s body is darker below and lighter above. This is unusual in aquatic animals which usually exhibit the opposite, as it helps with camouflage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Brazilian rainbow boa is named for its iridescent skin that refracts light and creates a rainbow-colored effect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sexual maturity in Brazilian rainbow boas is determined by length rather than age. Males may breed at 4 feet and females at 4.5 feet in length.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The name &quot;tarantula&quot; originated in the Renaissance period to refer to a small wolf spider from Taranto, Italy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are considered very calm and docile and, as a result, are one of the most popular and widespread tarantula species in the pet trade.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eastern newts consume aquatic insects, such as mosquitos. This is beneficial to humans, because&amp;nbsp;eastern newts may help to control insect populations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eastern newts&#039; skin is slightly toxic, which helps protect it from predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Flagtail characins migrate upriver to spawn.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female Fowler&#039;s toads lay eggs in strings with clutches of up to 20,000 eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female Philippine crocodiles build the nest that houses their eggs, but both males and females guard it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Philippine crocodile is one of the most endangered crocodilian species, with estimates of wild populations fewer than 100.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The radiated tortoise&#039;s shell&amp;nbsp;has&amp;nbsp;blood vessels and nerves so, like other tortoises, it can feel when it is being touched.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The spider tortoise, named for the yellow, web-like pattern of its shell,&amp;nbsp;is the smallest of four tortoises that live only on the island of Madagascar.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During the hot, dry season, these turtles aestivate, or go through a period of dormancy similar to hibernation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Despite their name, these pythons do not live on the island of Timor. They are found on the neighboring Lesser Sunda Islands.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Timor pythons are considered one of the most nervous and high-strung&amp;nbsp;pythons.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These geckos thrive in manmade environments, so they are sometimes utilized to control insects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have the remains of a rudimentary third eye on the top of their head, which scientists believe helps regulate their activity in different&amp;nbsp;light conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their ears are visible as small holes on both sides of the head, and you can actually see straight through their heads through their ears.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The coronated tree frog is the only species in this genus. Unlike many other tree frogs in the Hylidae family they lack finger webs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As tadpoles, they eat unfertilized eggs laid for them by the female. This is unusual for large tree frog species, but is also seen in several species of Dendrobates, as well as in the Jamaican laughing frog which is&amp;nbsp;also in the family Hylidae.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The species name &lt;em&gt;caerulea&lt;/em&gt; means blue in Latin. This is interesting because they are not usually seen as blue, but as bright green.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Extracts from the skin have medical uses such as fighting staphylococcus bacteria that can cause abscesses, lowering blood pressure and treating cold sores caused by the herpes virus.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Vietnamese mossy frogs will fold into a ball when frightened and play dead. Their predators include tree-dwelling mammals and snakes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are 11 species of Theloderma, all found in Southeast Asia. They all have bumpy skin and some sort of cryptic coloration. Other members of this group are brown and look like bark, and another species, the warty tree frog, looks like bird poop.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The warts behind smooth-sided toads&#039; eyes are called parotid glands. The parotid glands produce toxins that interfere with a predator&#039;s heart function and can cause death due to heart failure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Smooth-sided toads breed in permanent and temporary water bodies, some of which the adult toads dig themselves.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This family of toads cannot extend their tongues like other toads or frogs. To feed, they must leap forward and catch prey with their mouths.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their skin secretes a milky substance that irritates the mouth and eyes of attackers. A taste of the toxin usually deters predators from ever attaching again. However, grass snakes and other water serpents have been known to attack and devour these toads without ill effects.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lemur leaf frogs are able to change color at night when they are typically active.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These amphibians are territorial. Males call with a short “tick” to warn other males they are nearby.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lemur leaf frogs are able to change color at night when they are typically active.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These amphibians are territorial. Males call with a short “tick” to warn other males they are nearby.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden mantella frogs have evolved to be very similar in appearance and behavior to the poison frogs of South America (family Dendrobatidae).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden mantella frogs live in groups usually consisting of twice as many males as females&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden mantella frogs have evolved to be very similar in appearance and behavior to the poison frogs of South America (family Dendrobatidae).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Golden mantella frogs live in groups usually consisting of twice as many males as females&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The species name comes from the Mandarin words &quot;shan&quot; (mountain) and &quot;jing&quot; (spirit or demon).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A giant anteater&#039;s tongue is 2 feet long and&amp;nbsp;can flick in and out of its mouth 150 times per minute.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&#039;s coated in sticky saliva, which allows anteaters to slurp up ants and termites.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Research has found that giant anteaters can identify a particular species of ant or termite by smell before they rip apart a nest.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Porcupines are covered in about 30,000 quills. They cannot throw or shoot their quills. Because quills are so lightly attached, they come off easily when a predator encounters them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While porcupines spend most of the time on the ground, they are good climbers and regularly climb trees in search of food and occasionally even build nests in trees. They are also good swimmers.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Caracals are the fastest felids of their size! They are also excellent jumpers and climbers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are supremely acrobatic and can leap agilely into the air to bring down prey, such as guinea fowl, on the wing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bobcats are often confused with the other three lynx species. Bobcats live in warmer climates, while other lynx occupy cold, northern latitudes and are adapted to living through long winters and deep snow.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bobcats can run at up to 30 miles per hour. They place&amp;nbsp;their back feet in the same spots where their front feet have stepped to reduce noise when hunting.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Female lions&amp;nbsp;raise the cubs and are also the primary hunters.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Without their coats, lion and tiger bodies are so similar that only experts can tell them apart.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sumatran tigers are the smallest of the tiger subspecies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like a human fingerprint, no two tigers have the same pattern of stripes on their coats. Scientists can use these distinctions to identify tigers in the wild.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tigers are adept swimmers. They&amp;nbsp;often go into the water to escape flies or cool off, and can easily cross rivers and lakes 5 miles (8 km) wide.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sumatran tigers are the smallest of the tiger subspecies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like a human fingerprint, no two tigers have the same pattern of stripes on their coats. Scientists can use these distinctions to identify tigers in the wild.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tigers are adept swimmers. They&amp;nbsp;often go into the water to escape flies or cool off, and can easily cross rivers and lakes 5 miles (8 km) wide.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Catfish have taste receptors all over their bodies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The world record weight for a channel catfish was a 58-pound (26.3 kilograms) fish caught in South Carolina in 1964.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Domestic chickens are a subspecies of&amp;nbsp;red junglefowl &lt;em&gt;(Gallus gallus)&lt;/em&gt;,&amp;nbsp;a species native to southern Asia.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are more chickens on Earth than any other bird species.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term &quot;donkey&quot; comes from dun (the usual grayish-brown color) and the suffix &quot;ky&quot; meaning small. Male donkeys are called &quot;jacks,&quot; and females are &quot;jennets.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The donkey was first domesticated about six thousand years ago.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A common misconception is that koi are large goldfish; although koi and goldfish are both domesticated from carp, they are distinct species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While carp are popular with anglers, koi are bred for ornamental ponds. Koi and goldfish are the most popular freshwater, ornamental fish throughout the world.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The koi breeding industry can be quite lucrative, with rumors of individual show-quality koi selling for hundreds of thousands of dollars.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ossabow Island hogs had to adapt to the food cycle on the island, which provides little to eat during the spring season. They developed a unique biochemical system of fat metabolism, enabling them to store a larger proportion of fat than any other hog.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These hogs naturally have a form of low-grade, non-insulin-dependent diabetes, making them excellent medical research animals.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is believed that more than 6,000 years ago, alpacas were developed through selective breeding heavily influenced by the wild vicuna.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alpacas were fully domesticated by Andean people centuries before the Incas&amp;nbsp;as a source of fuel, meat and fiber for fabric.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cattle have panoramic vision, but their depth perception is only focused in a small forward view.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word cattle comes from the Old French word &lt;em&gt;chattle&lt;/em&gt;, which means &quot;possession.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A goat&#039;s eye has a rectangular pupil. It is believed that goats have excellent night vision.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A goat&#039;s digestive system works nonstop throughout its adult life, continually manufacturing&amp;nbsp;digestive juices and enzymes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rüppell&#039;s griffon vultures have been documented as having reached heights of over 36,000 feet (10,973 meters) above sea level. This discovery came at a cost; an individual was sucked into the engine of an aircraft flying at 36,100 feet (11,003 meters) above Cote d&#039;Ivoire.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The adaptation that allows this species to fly so high is an alteration of one of its proteins, which allows the bird to fly efficiently despite lower pressure and available oxygen.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The noticeable &quot;eyelashes&quot; of Abyssinian ground hornbills are actually modified feathers that protect their eyes from injury.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While they are able to fly, Abyssinian ground hornbills prefer to run if threatened. They will, however, fly to catch prey or defend territory.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fossils found in China and Uzbekistan, as well as a two million-year-old fossil found in South Africa, suggest that ancestral forms of Grevy&#039;s zebras were once widespread in Africa and Eurasia.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1882, Jules Grevy, the president of France, was given a zebra as a gift from the King of Abyssinia (what is now Ethiopia). A French zoologist realized that this type of zebra was different from other zebras and named the species after President Grevy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red river hogs are also called &quot;tufted pigs&quot; due to their long, white whiskers and tufts found on the ears.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They mark their territory, such as frequently used paths, using their tusks to scrape tree trunks, and using foot, neck and preorbital glands near their eyes to scent mark.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gazelles can often be observed bouncing into the air with all four hooves off the ground at the same time. This behavior is called stotting.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like North American white-tailed deer, lesser kudus&#039; tails are brown on top and white underneath and are held upright when the animal flees.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lesser kudu travel in impressive, bounding leaps, covering up to 30 feet (9 meters) at a time and reaching recorded heights exceeding 6.5 feet (2 meters).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cheetah is the single surviving species of the genus Acinonyx.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A cheetah&#039;s footprints have claw tips visible, more like a dog&#039;s than like a typical cat&#039;s print.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cheetahs have very low levels of genetic variation compared to other mammals, making them susceptible to disease. This genetic similarity may have developed due to of a severe population reduction, or bottleneck, that occurred about 10,000 years ago.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sitatunga&amp;nbsp;are swamp-dwelling antelopes and excellent swimmers. Their elongated, wide-splayed hooves help them walk on&amp;nbsp;soft terrain such as&amp;nbsp;swamps and marshes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If seriously alarmed,&amp;nbsp;sitatunga&amp;nbsp;sink below water to swim to deeper areas with only their nostrils above the surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To deal with desert heat, scimitar-horned oryx can tolerate an internal body temperature of 116 degrees Fahrenheit (47 C). This allows them to conserve water and thrive in the desert.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The scimitar-horned oryx is now extinct in the wild, though surveys show that Niger and Chad may have appropriate habitat for reintroduction, and some reintroductions have begun in Tunisia and Chad.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Maned wolf urine has a powerful aroma, reminding many humans of the way skunks smell.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The maned wolf is the largest canid of South America. It looks more like a long-legged fox than a wolf. Genetic studies show that it is neither fox nor true wolf, but a distinct species. It is the only member of its genus, Chrysocyon.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The flamingo&#039;s pink or red color comes from its&amp;nbsp;food, including algae and shrimp.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Flamingos often stand on one leg, with their head resting on their body and their other leg tucked under the abdomen. This posture cuts heat loss through the legs and feet.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Barred owls that prey heavily on crayfish can develop pink-tinged breast feathers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are expanding their range into the Pacific Northwest and have begun to hybridize with their smaller,&amp;nbsp;critically endangered cousin, the spotted owl.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The young can be aggressive&amp;nbsp;&lt;span&gt;—&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;regurgitating or defecating on human intruders.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Black-crowned night herons have been hunted for food, though they are hunted for this purpose much less frequently now. If they nest near human settlements, they are considered pests.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Primarily terrestrial birds, blue-billed curassows stick to the forest floor to eat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Only the female curassow has a knob on her bill.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Peafowl tend to walk or run rather than fly. They prefer to fly only in strong, short bursts to escape predators or to reach the tree tops in which they roost at night.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In Indian folklore, peafowl are believed to be important snake killers, able to hypnotize them and spoil the snakes&#039; eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The emu is a fast runner and can reach speeds of up to 31 mph (50 km/hr). Their long legs enable them to walk considerable distances or outrun danger. Emus are also strong swimmers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In emus, as in most ratites&lt;span&gt;—&lt;/span&gt;large flightless birds&lt;span&gt;—&lt;/span&gt;the male incubates the eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rheas have unusually long wings for flightless birds. They use their wings like an airplane rudder balance while running and to dodge predators.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rhea feathers are used to make feather dusters in South America.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The male rhea incubates the eggs and cares for the chicks after they hatch.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Macaws ingest mineralized sand and clay, which helps neutralize the toxins in the seeds and nuts they eat.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The king vulture spends hours soaring without flapping its wings. It flies much higher in the air than other species of vulture, which prefer to soar close to the treetops.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a&amp;nbsp;king vulture lands, other birds make way for it. Though it appears to dominate over a feeding site, this vulture actually relies on other, stronger-beaked carrion-eaters to initially rip open the hide of a carcass.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The kori bustard is one of the world&#039;s heaviest flying birds, however, it lives on the ground and is reluctant to fly unless in serious danger.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kori bustards are one of the few species of birds that drink water using a sucking motion rather than scooping.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The kiwi has&amp;nbsp;the second largest egg for body size of any bird—an average of 15&amp;nbsp;percent of its&amp;nbsp;body weight, compared to only 2 percent in the ostrich.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The kiwi is so remarkably unbirdlike in appearance and behavior that is has sometimes been referred to as an honorary &quot;mammal.&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The brown kiwi is the only bird known in which both the left and the right ovaries consistently occur—most birds have only one.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Southern swamp sparrows often conceal their nests made of fine grasses&amp;nbsp;between cattails or among other vegetation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They lay three to six greenish-white eggs with spotty brown marks and&amp;nbsp;lay two clutches of eggs each year.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The blue&amp;nbsp;crane is one of only two species of crane without red on its head.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The blue crane is the national bird of South Africa.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Clouded leopards can open their mouths to an impressive 100-degree angle!&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Clouded leopards are one of the few animals—and one of only two cat species—that can climb down trees headfirst.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Though there are many theories, scientists are not certain why giant pandas have their distinctive black-and-white markings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pandas are solitary animals&amp;nbsp;but will vocalize&amp;nbsp;during social interactions. They sometimes chirp, honk, bleat, chomp and bark.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sloth bears&#039; nostrils can close completely, protecting the animals from dust or insects when raiding termite nests or beehives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sloth bears are the only bears to routinely carry their young on their backs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their coat of tightly packed under-fur and long guard hairs&amp;nbsp;are water repellent. Air pockets within their coat keep them insulated and dry while under water, so it is very important that otters groom regularly and reintroduce air into their coats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their ears are small and, like their nostrils, can be closed while the animal swims under water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bison have an excellent sense of hearing and smell, but cannot see very well, so an entire herd can stampede if it is startled. Bison have cloven hoofs, and can reach speeds of 30 miles per hour (48 kilometers per hour).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bison shed their heavy winter coats in the spring, rolling on the ground to loosen the hair, which falls off in gobs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Fishing cats are most closely related to Pallas cats, rusty-spotted cats, leopard cats and flat-headed cats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike many cat species, fishing cats readily swim. Their front toes are partially webbed, and their claws protrude slightly even when retracted, an adaptation for fishing. Their round, elongated head is also adapted for diving.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Giant salamanders have amazing regenerative capabilities and are able to re-grow skin and bone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are one of the largest salamander species in the world, second only to Chinese giant salamanders.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Like other salamanders, they primarily &quot;breathe&quot; through their skin.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Though they are largely arboreal, spending much of their time in the trees, these monkeys will occasionally come to the ground to forage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Allen&#039;s swamp monkeys are highly social primates that communicate with members of their troops using gestures and calls.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have the unique ability among pollinators to open the traveler tree&#039;s flowers. While the lemurs benefit by eating the nectar within the flowers, the tree benefits from the pollination that occurs when the pollen sticks to the lemurs&#039; faces and is transported to the next tree.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hermit crab species come in a range of sizes, from a fraction of an inch to nearly the size of a coconut.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A crab may eat its molted shell, possibly for its calcium, vitamins and minerals.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike cats, rats can move their whiskers. They are able to move each one individually. Rats use their whiskers much in the same way humans use their hands to feel and sense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Brown rats are foragers and can survive on a huge range of foods. One study of a rat&#039;s stomach contents revealed over 4,000 different items.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Females experience a six-hour period of estrus, during which they mate as many as 500 times with multiple competing males.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lemurs establish and reinforce social bonds within groups through grooming. They have six lower teeth that stick straight out from the&amp;nbsp;jaw, forming a dental comb used to groom their own fur and that of other members of their social group.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A ring-tailed lemur mob will gather in open areas of the forest to sunbathe. They sit in what some call a &quot;yoga position&quot; with their bellies toward the sun and their arms and legs stretched out to the sides. This position maximizes the exposure of the less densely covered underside of the lemurs to the sun, warming them up before they forage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each ring-tailed lemur has exactly 13 alternating black and white bands on its tail.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When ring-tailed troops travel throughout their home range, they keep their tails raised in the air, like flags, to keep group members together.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Schmidt&#039;s red-tailed monkeys have large cheek pouches that can store almost as much food as their stomachs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These monkeys&amp;nbsp;are named for the red fur on their tails.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition to having distinctive fingerprints like humans do, gorillas also have unique nose prints.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gorillas are the largest of the great apes, but the western lowland gorilla is the smallest of the subspecies.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The most arboreal bear species, spectacled bears will build platforms to reach food high in trees or nests to sleep in.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While fishing, a brown pelican will fly up as high as 100 feet (30 meters), before folding back its wings and plunging into the sea. Brown pelicans are the only species of pelican that hunts with such dramatic plunging dives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In Florida, at least 500 pelicans are killed each year from entanglement in fishing gear, abandoned fishing lines, other marine debris and overhead wires.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Long, wide wings give bald eagles the ability to stay aloft and conserve energy by soaring.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Keen, full-color vision is their most developed sense, which they use to find prey.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Siamangs have a grayish or pinkish throat sac, which they inflate during vocalizations. The throat sac can become as large as a grapefruit.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When moving slowly, they swing like a pendulum as they grab one branch and release before grabbing the next, so that the body is freely projected through the air. Flights of 25 to 32 feet (8 to 10 meters) have been witnessed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Siamangs are fiercely territorial and defend their territory with daily singing rituals.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Vocalization is a major social investment for white-cheeked gibbons. The basic pattern of gibbon vocalization consists of an introductory sequence where both males and females &quot;warm up,&quot; followed by alternating sequences of male and female calls with female great calls. Vocalization sessions usually end with a male coda and are often accompanied by behavioral acrobatics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gibbons move and feed mainly in the upper and middle levels of the canopy and almost never come down to the ground, except at the Zoo where they seem often to prefer to spend more time on the ground.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Beavers are the largest rodents in North America and the second largest in the world (South America&#039;s capybaras being the heaviest).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A beaver&#039;s&amp;nbsp;teeth, which are orange due to their protective coating, grow continuously throughout its lifetime.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Beavers do not have the ability to burp, but they can pass gas.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A maternal den, for mothers and pups, is one of the only ways that wolves seek shelter; otherwise, they are out in the open for most of their lives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Wolves are the largest canine, one of the most social carnivores and are a keystone species--critical to their ecosystems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;More facts: &lt;a href=&quot;/animals/news/why-do-wolves-howl-and-other-top-wolf-questions-answered&quot;&gt;Why Do Wolves Howl? And Other Top Questions Answered&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike seals, sea lions primarily use their fore-flippers to propel themselves through the water. They also have visible ear-flaps, while seals only have ear holes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;California sea lions may struggle with a tendency to overheat. To cool off, they will rest with a flipper in the water, flip sand over their backs or fan their flippers in the water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On land, seals move like caterpillars by&amp;nbsp;alternately shifting weight from their chest to their pelvic region, or they roll to their destination. They appear quite clumsy and slow but can overtake a running human over a short distance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Seals see better underwater than above the surface.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Harbor seals can dive to depths of 500 feet (152.4 meters) but depths of up to 1,460 feet (446 meters) have been recorded. They can remain submerged for up to 30 minutes at a time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Before a deep dive, harbor seals slow their heart rates from upwards of 80 (averaging between 80 and 120) beats per minute to as few as three or four. After surfacing, the seal&#039;s heartbeat accelerates rapidly for a short time.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;While river otters tend to live alone or in pairs, they often socialize in groups and are known for their playful behavior.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Otters are playful creatures, frequently seen sliding down riverbanks or&amp;nbsp;burrowing through snow.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike other ducks, the hooded merganser almost always nests right next to water.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ravens are highly intelligent animals and can use their beaks to rip objects open, helping them find both food and shelter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ravens have been known to use tools to obtain food and aid&amp;nbsp;in defending their territories. Ravens and other corvid species are the subject of multiple cognitive research studies focusing on their ability to learn and use tools.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aldabra tortoises are easily domesticated and can learn to identify their keepers in a short time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Aldabra tortoises can reach ages of over 150 years.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As an alligator&#039;s teeth are worn down, they are replaced. An alligator can go through 3,000 teeth in a lifetime.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sex of the juveniles is determined by the temperature of the eggs. Temperatures of 31&amp;nbsp;C (87.8&amp;nbsp;F) or below produce females, 32&amp;nbsp;C (89.6&amp;nbsp;F) produces 75 percent males and 32.5&amp;nbsp;C (90.5&amp;nbsp;F) and above are mostly females.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Burmese pythons swallow prey whole. Their jaws separate and allow them to eat an animal four to five times as wide as their heads.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Chinese alligators dig extensive tunnels with multiple chambers, entrances and pools. Largely nocturnal because of human persecution, they stay in their tunnels much of the day when humans are in the vicinity, as well as during cool weather and winter months.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cuban crocodiles are strong swimmers and are adept at walking and leaping, which makes them equally at home in water or on land.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using powerful tail thrusts from below the water&#039;s surface, they can leap from the water to catch birds and mammals&amp;nbsp;from overhanging tree branches.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eastern indigo snakes are the longest snakes found in the U.S., reaching an average length&amp;nbsp;of 5-7 feet.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This snake is nonvenomous.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eastern red-backed salamanders can evade predators by dropping all or part of their tail in the event of an attack. In its place, a new tail will eventually grow, though this new tail may be duller in color.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lifespan for the eastern red-backed salamander is approximately 25 years in human care.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eyelash palm pitvipers have inadvertently been sent throughout the world in banana shipments.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eyelash palm pitvipers are ovoviviparous, which means the eggs develop inside the mother, then hatch out and are apparently born.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gaboon vipers are venomous. Their bite can be fatal, though they are calm and rarely bite humans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Their fangs can be 2 inches (5 centimeters) long, making them the longest fangs of any venomous snake.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word gharial is derived from the word ghara,&amp;nbsp;which means mud pot.&amp;nbsp;It was misread by Europeans who changed the word to gavial. Thus, this species is known both as gavial and gharial.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gharial eggs are the largest of any crocodilian species, weighing on average 6 ounces (160 grams).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Gila monster is one of only small number of venomous lizards (including the Mexican beaded lizard, the Komodo dragon and some Australian species).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rather than injecting venom through hollow fangs like venomous snakes, Gilas have enlarged, grooved teeth in their lower jaw. When they bite, their powerful jaws chew the venom in through capillary action along the grooves in these teeth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Anacondas are a source of many myths that exaggerate their size and attacks on humans. Substantiated reports of giant constrictors actually killing and eating humans are quite rare.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green salamanders are largely inactive from about December to April.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In a phenomenon known as parallel evolution, green tree pythons looks and acts much like a South American relative, the emerald tree boa, to which it is not closely related. Though the resemblance in appearance and behavior is strong, there are significant differences as well. For instance, the boa bears live young, whereas the python lays eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Green tree pythons may have more than 100 teeth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hellbenders have lungs, but they are largely non-functional (vestigial). Instead hellbenders breathe using several loose flaps of thick wrinkled skin running along their sides. They absorb up to 95 percent of their oxygen through their skin, primarily through these folds and wrinkles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mucus covers hellbenders&#039; bodies, which may help protect them from abrasion and parasites. It is also distasteful to potential predators.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the United States, research on cobra venom has yielded pain relievers such as Cobroxin, used to block nerve transmission and Nyloxin, used for severe arthritis pain.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Snake charmers do not really hypnotize cobras with their flute music. It&#039;s often a sad con game in which an exhausted cobra is put on the defensive, yet conditioned (with pain) not to strike the flutist.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Komodo dragons can briefly run at speeds of up to 13 mph (20 kph).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When threatened, they can throw up the contents of their stomachs to lessen their weight in order to flee.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Long-tailed salamanders court by rubbing their heads together before mating.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Painted terrapins cannot excrete salt from their bodies, which means they can live only in freshwater, or brackish water with low salinity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Compared to many other turtle species, the painted terrapin has a small clutch size (10 to 12 eggs). This, combined with a limited range of nesting beaches, makes it easier for poachers to find and capture individuals and collect their eggs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Even just-hatched copperheads have fully functional fangs capable of injecting venom that is just as toxic as an adult&#039;s&amp;nbsp;venom.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The copperhead is the cause of many snakebites yearly, but these bites&amp;nbsp;are rarely fatal and typically occur when the snake is stepped on or accidentally touched.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Studies have shown that Panamanian golden frogs have enough toxins in their skin to kill more than 1,000 mice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They get their toxins from the insects they eat in the wild. The Zoo&#039;s golden frogs are fed different insects, so they are safe for keepers and researchers to handle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Studies have shown that Panamanian golden frogs have enough toxins in their skin to kill more than 1,000 mice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They get their toxins from the insects they eat in the wild. The Zoo&#039;s golden frogs are fed different insects, so they are safe for keepers and researchers to handle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red pandas share the giant panda&#039;s pseudo-thumb, a modified wrist bone used to grasp bamboo when feeding.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In very cold temperatures, red pandas can become dormant, lowering their metabolic rate and raising it every few hours as they wake up to look for food.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Red pandas are the only living member of the family &lt;em&gt;Ailuridae&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
